ma1010_AskIntent_QA
Enter From (All Channels)
ma1015_IntentMapper_IM
Enter From (Default Channel)
ma1025_PlayMainMenu_MSma1005_Greeting_MS
Default Channel
  • The next step is to collect the user's intent. This question and answer node works with a companion intent mapper node, which routes the intent to the corresponding destination. Because this is a demo app, we've included an option for the user to get a list of things they can do in the system (that is, "What are my options?"). We handle this option as a command override ("options" is a value of eGlobalCommands, the global command entity for this project). Check out the optional Command Overrides section, under User Input. Additionally, notice that some messages are intentionally blank for the Digital VA text channel, since, in this case, the VA goes straight to question and answer node ma1013_MenuOptions_QA to explicitly list out all available options on the first step. Messages that only have TTS but no rich text version are only used in the Voice VA version of the bot (IVR channel), and not in the Digital VA text version.

ma1010_AskIntent_QA
Default Channel
  • This node illustrates how we can support both directed dialog and open dialog. We give the user a set of menu options (directed dialog), while also collecting the NLU intent (open dialog) so the user isn't limited to just these options—they can tell us any intent within the NLU grammar. We handle the menu options as command overrides ("book flight", "flight status", and "lost luggage" are values of eGlobalCommands, the global command entity for this project). Under User Input, check out the Collect section, and the optional DTMF and Command Overrides sections. We set this up for all channels but, in real life, this would normally apply to IVR integrations only.

bf1055_SubmitFlight_DA
This data access node is called when the user has confirmed they would like to book the proposed itinerary. An outside endpoint is called using the flight information, and a Boolean response is returned. In the Integration section, "Enable client-side fetching" is selected. This means that it is assumed that the client that will run this bot knows what to do with, and how to respond to this data access request. Note: When you try this app with the Mix demo client, it already knows to map the name of this data access node to this backend function path: demo.mix.nuance.com/api/book-flight-quickstart
